{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:14:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:14:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18417"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18417"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74528"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11135"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60019"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8405"},{"type":"tags","id":"9982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25811"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74528"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cytokines contributes to the browning of adipose tissue in cancer cachexia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IL1 and IL6","PTHrP and IL1","TNFa and IL6","TNFa and IL1","PTHrP and IL6"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the context of cancer cachexia, browning of adipose tissue is observed. This process is influenced by specific cytokines. In cancer cachexia, the browning of white adipose tissue is a process where white fat cells take on characteristics of brown fat cells, including increased thermogenesis. This process is influenced by specific cytokines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPTHrP and IL6\u003C/strong\u003E are key cytokines involved in the browning of adipose tissue in cancer cachexia. Parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP) has been shown to induce browning, while interleukin-6 (IL-6) is a pro-inflammatory cytokine that also contributes to this process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIL1 and IL6\u003C/strong\u003E are both pro-inflammatory cytokines, but IL1 is not specifically associated with the browning of adipose tissue in cancer cachexia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETNFa and IL6\u003C/strong\u003E are both involved in inflammation and cachexia, but TNFa is more associated with muscle wasting rather than browning of adipose tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETNFa and IL1\u003C/strong\u003E are both pro-inflammatory cytokines, but neither is specifically linked to the browning of adipose tissue in cancer cachexia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the role of cytokines in cancer cachexia can help in developing targeted therapies to mitigate weight loss and muscle wasting in affected patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cancer cachexia is associated with the browning of white adipose tissue, which is influenced by specific cytokines.","Parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP) and interleukin-6 (IL-6) are key cytokines involved in the browning of adipose tissue in cancer cachexia.","Understanding the role of cytokines in cancer cachexia can help in developing targeted therapies."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health 